-- Wheat Jumps After Large Purchase by China: Commodities at Close
-- B y   T h o m a s   G a l a t o l a
-- 2013-04-08T20:53:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-08/wheat-jumps-after-large-purchase-by-china-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI Spot
Index of 24  raw materials  rose 0.6 percent to settle at 632.31
at 3:45 p.m.  New York  time, led by wheat.  The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  gauge  of 26 prices advanced 0.6
percent to 1,507.48.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Wheat rose to a one-week high following a report that  China 
bought about 960,000 metric tons of the grain from the U.S.,
where low temperatures threatened winter crops.  China, the top wheat consumer, bought the soft red-winter
variety last week, state-owned Grain.gov.cn said today in a
report without disclosing its sources. Shipments from the  Gulf
of Mexico  will be from June to December, according to the
report. Cold expected this week in the southern U.S. Great
Plains may curb yields, Commodity Weather Group said.  On the Chicago Board of Trade, wheat futures for May
delivery rose 1.9 percent to $7.125 a bushel. Earlier, the price
reached $7.16, the highest for a most-active contract since
March 28.  Corn futures for May delivery rose 0.7 percent to $6.335 a
bushel.  Soybean futures advanced 1.2 percent to $13.78 a bushel,
the biggest gain since March 21.  CRUDE OIL  Crude oil rose amid clashes in  Nigeria , while nuclear talks
between  Iran  and world powers ended without agreement.  On the  New York Mercantile Exchange , oil futures for May
delivery increased 0.7 percent to $93.36 a barrel.  Brent oil for May settlement gained 0.5 percent to $104.66
a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures Europe exchange.  Vitol Group sold a cargo of Forties crude in the North Sea
market to Morgan Stanley, bringing the sales total to seven
since March 28.  Daily shipments of North Sea crude for loading in May will
drop by 5 percent from April, according to programs obtained by
 Bloomberg News .  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline rebounded on speculation that last week’s drop,
the most in six months, was overdone.  On the Nymex, gasoline futures for May delivery gained 1.6
percent to $2.9093 a gallon. Last week, the price tumbled 7.8
percent, the most since Oct. 5.  Ultra low-sulfur-diesel futures for May delivery climbed
1.5 percent to $2.9537 a gallon.  BASE METALS  Copper advanced the most in more than two weeks as miners
prepared to strike in  Chile , the world’s biggest producer.  On the Comex in New York, copper futures for May delivery
rose 0.8 percent to $3.371 a pound, the biggest gain since March
22.  On the London Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months climbed 0.6 percent to $7,450 a metric ton ($3.38 a
pound). Tin, lead, aluminum, nickel and zinc gained.  LIVESTOCK  Cattle advanced the most in a week on speculation that
demand for U.S. beef is increasing.  On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, cattle futures for June
delivery climbed 0.4 percent to $1.22025 a pound, the biggest
increase since March 28.  Feeder-cattle futures for May settlement gained 0.3 percent
to $1.4475 a pound.  Hog futures for June settlement rose 0.9 percent to close
at 90.55 cents a pound.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas slipped from a 20-month high on forecasts of
warmer weather in the eastern U.S. that would limit demand for
the heating fuel.  On the Nymex, gas futures for May delivery dropped 1
percent to $4.082 per million British thermal units.  U.K. gas dropped as warmer temperatures cut demand for the
heating fuel. The same-day price fell 7.6 percent to 73.75 pence
a therm at 4:12 p.m. in  London , according to broker prices
compiled by Bloomberg. A therm is 100,000 Btu.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold declined for the fourth time in five sessions as the
dollar’s rebound reduced the appeal of the metal as an
alternative investment.  On the Comex, gold futures for June delivery slipped 0.2
percent to $1,572.50 an ounce.  Silver futures for May delivery dropped 0.3 percent to
$27.138 an ounce.  On the Nymex, platinum futures for July delivery added 0.1
percent to $1,537 an ounce.  Palladium futures for June delivery advanced 0.8 percent to
$729.80 an ounce. Last week, the price tumbled 5.8 percent, the
most since May.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Coffee fell the most in a month on signs of ample global
supplies, led by surging yields in  Brazil , the world’s top
producer.  On ICE Futures U.S. in New York, arabica coffee for May
delivery plunged 3 percent to $1.359 a pound, the biggest slide
since March 5.  Orange-juice futures for May delivery declined 1.6 percent
to $1.4545 a pound.  Cotton futures for May delivery sank 1.6 percent to 85.38
cents a pound.  Raw-sugar futures for May delivery rose 0.3 percent to 17.7
cents a pound  Cocoa futures for May delivery jumped 2.5 percent to $2,185
a ton.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Thomas Galatola in New York at 
